Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Dangote Sugar, Naiade Resorts, Sasini Are Movers

-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a   a n d   K a m l e s h   B h u c k o r y
-- 
2011-02-16T16:36:37Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-16/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-dangote-sugar-naiade-resorts-sasini-are-movers.html
Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index slumped for a second day, declining 0.5 percent to
26,468.58 at the 2:30 p.m. close, according to an e-mailed
statement from the bourse.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index snapped five days of gains,
falling less than 0.1 percent to 2,072.96 at the 1:30 p.m. close
of trading in Port Louis. Kenya’s All-Share Index dropped 0.3
percent to 78.09 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi. Namibia’s
FTSE  Namibia Overall Index  slid 1 percent to 913.89 by 5 p.m. in
Windhoek. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index decreased 0.3
percent to 1,049.99 at the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.    Dangote Sugar Refinery Plc  (DANGSUGA NL), Nigeria’s second-
largest manufacturer of the sweetener, slid 0.5 percent to 15.2
naira, a second day of declines, after its price estimate was
cut by 7 percent to 16.2 naira at CSL Stockbrokers.    Naiade Resorts Ltd . (NRL MP), a Mauritian hotel operator,
advanced the most in two weeks after a shareholder withdrew an
application for an injunction on Naiade’s rights offer. The
stock rallied 3.7 percent to 26 rupees, the biggest jump since
Jan. 31.    Sasini Ltd . (STCL KN), a Kenyan tea and coffee grower,
climbed 0.4 percent to 12.2 shillings, gaining for a third day.
African tea prices rose for the first week in four, climbing 3.3
percent to an average of $2.79 a kilogram at a weekly sale in
Mombasa, Kenya, Tea Brokers East Africa Ltd. said in an e-mailed
statement today.  To contact the reporters on this story:
